<div id="review_3544935732" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3544935732" />
    <a title="Hadrian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4100763-hadrian"><img alt="Hadrian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1556569510p2/4100763.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3544935732?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hadrian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hadrian" href="/user/show/4100763-hadrian">Hadrian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143039341" href="/book/show/527174.The_Moon_and_Sixpence">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4100763-hadrian?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4100763-hadrian?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4100763-hadrian?shelf=visual-arts">visual-arts</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3544935732" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14259645968756345749">The Moon and Sixpence, I was surprised to find, enjoys greater popularity in China now than it does in the Anglophone world. Only look at how many reviews there are on Douban for a sample. I&apos;ve heard of a manager who, when asked about the book, said, &quot;If you catch an employee reading that, they&apos;re going to quit.&quot;<br/><br/>How so? It&apos;s loosely based on the life of Paul Gauguin. This novel&apos;s Gauguin, a Charles Strickland, was a stockbroker who quits his ordinary life to go to France and then Tahiti to do ar</span>
  <span id="freeText14259645968756345749" style="display:none">The Moon and Sixpence, I was surprised to find, enjoys greater popularity in China now than it does in the Anglophone world. Only look at how many reviews there are on Douban for a sample. I've heard of a manager who, when asked about the book, said, "If you catch an employee reading that, they're going to quit."<br /><br />How so? It's loosely based on the life of Paul Gauguin. This novel's Gauguin, a Charles Strickland, was a stockbroker who quits his ordinary life to go to France and then Tahiti to do art. Those who praise the book admire this protagonist's independent thinking, his total disregard for others' opinions, and frankly as a kind of escapism from the pressures and monotony of a materialist society. Those who dislike the book do so for many reasons - that Strickland is a disgusting character who doesn't care what other people think, his casual cruelty towards women, his mistreatment of the natives of Tahiti, his sponging off of his friends, and his total lack of responsibility for his wife and children. <br /><br />It's a clever picture, so clever by half. It's a story about the mythologizing of the genius artist, and Maugham knows enough to talk about the people who have to support that art else that becomes the starving artist. It's an accumulation of clever minor details, and I'm sympathetic to his prose style, but also I have to marvel at the coldness of it all. A Gauguin we <u>might</u> forgive in a few decades, and because his paintings were so good. But if we know one now we might be lucky to put sixpence in their cup next to the subway stop.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14259645968756345749" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


