    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2680643234" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2680643234" />
    <a title="WhatIReallyRead" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52500467-whatireallyread"><img alt="WhatIReallyRead" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483674713p2/52500467.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2680643234?book_show_action=true">Feb 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="WhatIReallyRead" class="user" itemprop="url" name="WhatIReallyRead" href="/user/show/52500467-whatireallyread">WhatIReallyRead</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52500467-whatireallyread?shelf=art">art</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52500467-whatireallyread?shelf=owned-ebook">owned-ebook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52500467-whatireallyread?shelf=freebie">freebie</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52500467-whatireallyread?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52500467-whatireallyread?shelf=read-in-english">read-in-english</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52500467-whatireallyread?shelf=e-book">e-book</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52500467-whatireallyread?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52500467-whatireallyread?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52500467-whatireallyread?shelf=great-writing">great-writing</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2680643234" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10476970856343017818">The Moon and Sixpence is a novel that examines the life of a fictional artist Charles Strickland whose character is based on Paul Gauguin. <br/><br/>The story of Strickland&apos;s life is told through the first-person account by his friend, a fictional writer. Strickland is a misunderstood artist tortured by his inner demons and the people around him are hurt by the flying debris of the struggle. <br/><br/>The atmosphere in this book reminded me of <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/4750._mile_Zola' title='Émile Zola' rel='nofollow noopener'>Émile Zola</a>&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28409.The_Masterpiece' title='The Masterpiece by Émile Zola' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Masterpiece</a> which I read several months ago. Tragic obs</span>
  <span id="freeText10476970856343017818" style="display:none">The Moon and Sixpence is a novel that examines the life of a fictional artist Charles Strickland whose character is based on Paul Gauguin. <br /><br />The story of Strickland's life is told through the first-person account by his friend, a fictional writer. Strickland is a misunderstood artist tortured by his inner demons and the people around him are hurt by the flying debris of the struggle. <br /><br />The atmosphere in this book reminded me of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/4750._mile_Zola" title="Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">Émile Zola</a>'s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28409.The_Masterpiece" title="The Masterpiece by Émile Zola" rel="nofollow noopener">The Masterpiece</a> which I read several months ago. Tragic obsession seems to echo in all of the fictional painters' lives. It also featured a writer, the friend of the artist, who's loosely based on the author. I want to get to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/228089.Honor__de_Balzac" title="Honoré de Balzac" rel="nofollow noopener">Honoré de Balzac</a>'s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/817790.The_Unknown_Masterpiece" title="The Unknown Masterpiece by Honoré de Balzac" rel="nofollow noopener">The Unknown Masterpiece</a> as well and see if touches upon the same themes.<br /><br />I think the best feature of this book is the <b>brilliant writing</b>. I'll definitely read more by Maugham! <br /><br />In Part I we are immersed in the life and circumstances of Strickland and the people around him. It was focused on art and artists generally and Strickland as an example. Heartbreaking things happen and you can't help but be moved. The narrator shares a lot of beautiful musings about art and writing. I enjoyed the first part of The Moon and Sixpence more than the second. <br /><br />Towards the end of the book, the narrative became more disjointed, there were side-stories sprinkled in (like Abraham's and Tiare's). It's understandable, given the fact that the chosen perspective witnessed the events of Part I, but not Part II. Still, it didn't feel as immersive to me. Also, Part II seemed to be more focused on events, personal life, and felt more like gossip.<br /><br />To see how close of a parallel Strickland is to real-life Gauguin I also read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28206800.Gauguin" title="Gauguin by Ingo F. Walther" rel="nofollow noopener">Gauguin</a> - which is a non-fiction biography and artwork analysis. After that, I read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/249798.Gauguin_s_Intimate_Journals" title="Gauguin's Intimate Journals by Paul Gauguin" rel="nofollow noopener">Gauguin's Intimate Journals</a> to get a glimpse of his outlook on the events. <br /><br />A couple of things gave me pause:<br /><br />Strickland is described as such a jerk, most of his dialogue is "go to hell". But so many people are drawn to him, he has friends and people willing to help him all the time, even though he keeps pushing everyone away. Why is that? Even the narrator, who is a long way from Stroeve, displays this pattern. Why?<br /><br />There's a lot of commentary on Strickland's cruelty towards women. But I think it's important to note that the narrator omits (because he doesn't know) what happens behind closed doors between Strickland and his women. I doubt that he has always just continually kicked them and they became totally and helplessly devoted. One could have been a masochist, but not all. I don't think they would all respond with mad love to complete cruelty. He must have displayed a lot of passion at least at one time to each of them. By contrast, his later coldness made the women cling in hopes to revive the fire. But this wouldn't have happened without the initial fire. He wasn't saying "go to hell" to them all the time.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Another thing: Ata is madly in love and doesn't care if she catches the disease from Charles. Ok. But HOW IN THE WORLD doesn't she care if her kids do? How does she seem so uncaring that one of her children died? Were mothers back in the day so blasé about their children? I would have thought motherhood would be the one thing to bring a madly in love woman to her senses. This bothered me much more than Strickland's behavior. It's unpleasant but not unheard of to not return a woman's love; it's okay to sacrifice yourself to care for a loved one. Not loving one's children and sacrificing them for love seems just savage to me! <br /><br />About Blanche and Stroeve: The story of how they got married contributed a lot to my understanding of what happened. Stroeve always liked to imagine himself "saving" her (and Strickland), and couldn't let go of that role, no matter how much dignity he lost in the process. And she turned out to be an outwardly sensible woman who inwardly was rutinely given to wild fantasies about men who didn't care. And hysterically suicidal when forced to part with those fantasies. Initially, I was very sorry for them, but in the end what happened made sense.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="10476970856343017818" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


