  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3531854755" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3531854755" />
    <a title="booklady" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/350218-booklady"><img alt="booklady" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609115994p2/350218.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3531854755?book_show_action=true">Sep 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="booklady" class="user" itemprop="url" name="booklady" href="/user/show/350218-booklady">booklady</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Leather Bound " href="/book/show/13643972-the-moon-and-sixpence">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/350218-booklady?shelf=art">art</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/350218-booklady?shelf=2020">2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/350218-booklady?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3531854755" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10034231643415353393">There’s no denying Maugham’s ability as a writer. It’s a well-written book. But is it a novel or a biographical-novel, i.e., a novel based on a real person? I wanted it to be one or the other. It isn’t satisfying as either. It purports to be a novel loosely based on the life of the artist, Paul Gauguin. So, how loosely? How much of it can the reader believe in? Does that matter? If character matters to you, then the truth of the stories also matters. <br/><br/>Based on only the most cursory reading of Gau</span>
  <span id="freeText10034231643415353393" style="display:none">There’s no denying Maugham’s ability as a writer. It’s a well-written book. But is it a novel or a biographical-novel, i.e., a novel based on a real person? I wanted it to be one or the other. It isn’t satisfying as either. It purports to be a novel loosely based on the life of the artist, Paul Gauguin. So, how loosely? How much of it can the reader believe in? Does that matter? If character matters to you, then the truth of the stories also matters. <br /><br />Based on only the most cursory reading of Gauguin's life, Maugham’s fictional Charles Stickland (who is supposed to be Gauguin) deviates enough as to make the two men morally distinct. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Maugham’s Strickland undergoes a redemptive suffering at the end of his life which even convinces his first family that, <i>‘The mills of God grind slowly, but they grind exceedingly small.’ (Though with patience He stands waiting, with exactness grinds He all.) </i>― Henry Wadsworth Longellow This is not the case with Gauguin who instead of dying slowly and suffering quietly and without aid of pain relief as does Maugham’s Strickland of leprosy, dies (most likely) of a heart attack brought on by overdose of laudanum for treating syphilis. There was an empty bottle by his bedside when he was found dead. Our well-intentioned author wanted to present his painter in a favorable light. Well he may. But I, as his reader, am left to wonder. The painter is redeemed. His first wife and children who he abandoned are condemned for forgiving him because he became ‘a genius’. In point of fact, Gauguin, survived three of his children.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Was he ‘a genius’? Look up his paintings if you are not familiar with them. My edition of Maugham’s book was divided between two artists: Frederic Dorr Steele and Paul Gauguin. Personally, I preferred the first artist, Steele, though probably unknown to you and most of the world, does excellent black and white sketches, which for all their simplicity, are more appealing, realistic and arresting than anything produced by Gauguin though he spent his life chasing ‘Beauty’. Beauty is—after all—in the eye of the beholder. But I do promise that I tried to see what the author saw in Gauguin and his painting and could not.<br /><br />The three stars are based on Maugham’s writing ability minus my lack of trust in the result.<br /><br /><br />Have started to read this a couple of times but didn't get very far, but finally I think I am past the hump... Can't help it though I will never like Gauguin's painting... 😖 and that his personality matches it makes this hard to read...</span>
  <a data-text-id="10034231643415353393" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


